In [103]:
# Calculate Word Frequencies

# Create a dictionary to store the word frequencies by continent

word_freq_by_continent = pd.DataFrame()
filtered_tokens_by_continent = {}

for continent in data['Continent'].unique():
    continent_data = data[data['Continent'] == continent]
    all_tokens = [token for tokens in continent_data['Tokens'] for token in tokens]
    filtered_tokens = pd.Series([token.text for token in all_tokens if
                       not token.is_stop and not token.is_punct and not token.is_space and token.text.isalpha()])
    filtered_tokens_by_continent[continent] = filtered_tokens
    word_freq = pd.Series(filtered_tokens).value_counts()
    word_freq_by_continent[continent] = word_freq

word_freq_by_continent.replace(np.nan, 0, inplace=True)


print("Word Frequencies by Continent")
word_freq_by_continent

# Word Cloud for each continent

from wordcloud import WordCloud

wc = WordCloud(width=800, height=400, max_words=200, background_color='white')
for continent in data['Continent'].unique():

    wc.generate(' '.join(filtered_tokens_by_continent[continent]))

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))

    plt.imshow(wc, interpolation='bilinear')
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.title(f"Word Cloud for {continent}")
    plt.show()

  2. We can see what each continent is valued for by looking at the word frequencies.
In [105]:
# Word Count by Continent

avg_word_count_by_continent = {}

for continent in data['Continent'].unique():
    continent_data = data[data['Continent'] == continent]
    token_count = continent_data["Tokens"].map(lambda x: len(x))
    avg_word_count_by_continent[continent] = token_count.mean()

print("Average Word Count by Continent")

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 3))
sns.barplot(x=list(avg_word_count_by_continent.keys()), y=list(avg_word_count_by_continent.values()))

Convert Text to Numerical & Scale Data¶

In [106]:
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(max_features=100)
X_train = vectorizer.fit_transform(data['Tokens'].map(lambda x: ' '.join([token.text for token in x]))).toarray()

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)

X_scaled

In [107]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

# Apply K-Means with k=6 (initial assumption)
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=6, random_state=111, n_init='auto')
data['KMeans_Cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)

# Plot cluster distribution
sns.countplot(x=data['KMeans_Cluster'])
plt.title("Distribution of Anthems by K-Means Clusters")
plt.show()

Clustering by using hierarchical clustering visualized with a dendrogram¶

In [108]:
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import dendrogram, linkage, fcluster

Z = linkage(X_scaled, method='ward')


plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
dendrogram(Z, labels=data['Country'].values, leaf_rotation=90, leaf_font_size=8)
plt.title("Dendrogram for Anthem Clustering")
plt.xlabel("Countries")
plt.ylabel("Distance")
plt.show()

In [110]:
# Finding optimal number of clusters using the Elbow Method
inertia = []
k_range = range(1, 15)
for k in k_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=111, n_init='auto')
    kmeans.fit(X_scaled)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(k_range, inertia, marker='o')
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters (K)")
plt.ylabel("Inertia")
plt.title("Elbow Method for Optimal K")
Out[110]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Elbow Method for Optimal K')

Elbow Method Finding¶

The elbow method suggests that the optimal number of clusters is 8. After that the inertia decreases at a slower linear rate.

In [111]:
# Re-run K-Means with 8 clusters

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=8, random_state=111, n_init='auto')
data['KMeans_Cluster_Elbow_8'] = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)

# Plot cluster distribution
sns.countplot(x=data['KMeans_Cluster_Elbow_8'])
plt.title("Distribution of Anthems by K-Means Clusters")
plt.show()
